data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "Expected 3, got 1" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.Contains(...)` | Asserts membership directly |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` for the predicate check is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" method, so `IsTrue` is appropriate there.

Also consider sealing your test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
